Daimler, Impresa, Siemens, Vergnet: European Equity Preview

-- B y   J e f f   K e a r n s
-- 
2011-04-18T04:00:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-14/daimler-impresa-siemens-european-equity-preview-correct-.html
The following companies’ shares may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx  Europe  600 Index fell 0.5 percent to 277.01. The
Stoxx 50 Index retreated 0.5 percent to 2,602.66. The Euro Stoxx
50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, lost 1.1
percent to 2,917.72.  Carrefour SA (CA)  : The world’s second-largest retailer
said it’s selling 49 percent of BSF Holding to Itau Unibanco for
315 million euros ($456 million). The agreement is part of a
joint venture between the companies. Carrefour shares slipped
1.3 percent to 31.04 euros.  Corporacion Financiera Alba SA (ALB SM): The financial
holding company said it will pay an extraordinary dividend of 3
euros per share. The shares gained 0.1 percent to 43.02 euros.  Daimler AG (DAI)  : The German carmaker forecast revenue
of 1 billion euros ($1.5 billion) from its Car2go car sharing
unit,  Auto-Motor-und-Sport  reported, citing Chief Executive
Officer Dieter Zetsche. The shares fell 2.6 percent to 49.79
euros.  Electricite de  France  SA (EDF FP): EDF Energies Nouvelles
Reparties, owned equally by EDF Energies Nouvelles SA and  EDF
SA (EDF) , agreed to sell its 50 percent stake in French solar module
maker and installer Tenesol to oil and gas company  Total SA (FP)  . EDF shares shed 1.8 percent to 27.21 euros. Total stock
declined 1 percent to 41.64 euros.  Impresa SGPS SA (IPR)  : Ongoing Strategy Investments SGPS
SA, a Portuguese investment company, is considering whether to
keep its stake in the TV broadcaster and publisher, Ongoing
Chairman Nuno Vasconcellos said in a telephone interview.
Impresa dropped 1 percent to 99 euro cents.  Sanofi-Aventis SA (SAN)  : France’s biggest drugmaker,
will focus on growing and strengthening its internal businesses,
since the company is well-placed to avoid being impacted by a
“patent cliff,” Chief Executive Officer Chris Viehbacher said
in an interview with CNBC. The shares slipped 0.5 percent to
51.17 euros.  Siemens AG (SIE)  : Europe’s largest engineering company
may receive train orders from  Deutsche Bahn  AG worth 5 billion
euros ($7.24 billion),  dpa-afx  reported, citing unidentified
people familiar with the contract. Deutsche Bahn’s supervisory
board will meet April 21 to approve the order, the  news agency 
said. Siemens will deliver between 200 and 300 trains within the
next years, according to dpa-afx. The shares fell 0.6 percent to
93.20 euros.  Vergnet (ALVER)  SA: The maker of windmills said its
full-year loss narrowed to 6.8 million euros from 9.4 million
euros in 2009, and that it expects a “progressive return to
profitability” with sales of more than 120 million euros in
2011. The shares lost 2.9 percent to 4.96 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jeff Kearns in  New York  at 
 jkearns3@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Baker at   nbaker7@bloomberg.net . 